lead_paragraph: A sampling of noteworthy musical presentations for the holiday season at churches and concert halls in New York City, selected by Vivien Schweitzer. abstract: Selective listings from theater critics of The New York Times.
snippet: Selective listings from theater critics of The New York Times.
lead_paragraph: ‘PETER AND THE WOLF’ Lots of holiday shows rope in their victims with false promises of “fun for all ages.” But it’s hard to see how a theatrical event that includes miniature paper sculptures of animals, George Manahan conducting the Juilliard Ensemble and (this is important) Isaac Mizrahi could fail to delight anybody.

abstract: My third-floor study here in Washington looks out toward the old Naval Observatory a few blocks away. The Vice President currently lives inside the gates of the new Observatory — an 1890s improvement that took the astronomers to higher ground. This older one sprang from the vision of John Quincy Adams, who called for it in his 1825 State of the Union message. It wasn’t his fault that the choice of a site — a malarial patch of land so often fogged over that the astronomers couldn’t see anything — fell to one of his successors, John Tyler, more than fifteen years later.

abstract: PARIS — "Merry Christmas" may not be the most original greeting in the world, Neil Papworth admits today, but as he was about to send the world's first text message to a cellphone, it struck him as fittingly festive, certainly more so than "Mr. Watson, come here," the first words spoken over the telephone.
